0 GUILDS SOCIETY~

Guilds are groups of players who have joined together in a "team".  Guilds
contain up to 30 people in all.  Guilds may build a guildhall if they have
the money and these act as protected bases of operations for the guild.

RULES
You may only have one guilded character at any given time.
Guilds must always have five or more people in them.

FORMING A GUILD
You must have 5 people of level 25 or higher to form a guild.  When all five
are online, petition to the Gods and wait for a response.

COMMANDS
Command      Syntax               Function
kickout      soc k <player>       Kicks someone out of the guild.  You must
                                  have officer or higher rank and you can't
                                  boot someone of equal or higher rank.
enroll       soc e <player>       Enrolls an applicant into the guild.  They
                                  have to apply before they can be enrolled.
exile        soc exile <player>   Exiles someone from the guild.  They cannot
                                  join another guild without god intervention.
                                  Leader only command.
apply        soc a <player>       Applies to the target player's guild.  Only
                                  one application can be in at a time.
secede       soc s <player>       Leave your current guild.
deposit      soc d <amount>       Deposit money in the guild bank account.
demote       soc demote <player>  Demotes someone a rank within the guild.
                                  You must be higher in rank than the person
                                  who is being demoted.
decline      soc decline <player> Declines the current guild applicant.
promote      soc p <player>       Promotes someone a rank within the guild.
                                  You must be higher in rank than the person
                                  in order to promote them.
withdraw     soc w <amount>       Allows you to withdraw money from the guild.
                                  Deputy or leader only.
ostracize    soc o <player>       Ostracizes the player from the guild, making
                                  him an enemy.  Ostracized lists are displayed
                                  when you view the people in your guild.

gcc - Allows you to use the guild chat channel.

There are seven guild "rankings":

0.   EXILED
1.   PAROLE
2.   NORMAL
3.   SENIOR
4.   OFFICER
5.   DEPUTY
6.   LEADER

New members come into the guild at rank 2.

See also: GCC, GUILDHALLS
~

56 'GUILD CREATION' MAKECLAN~

To create a guild, you use the command
makeclan <clan_name>

This name should be something short and sweet, easy to remember.  It'll be
the filename, nothing more.  The who name is something different, and is set
after creation.  So if you're creating something like Disciples of Hate you
would use makeclan disciples, because you don't want to have to type a huge
long name whenever you want to stat, set, or play with the guild.

When you create a guild, the makeclan command tells you what you need to 
set next.  Generally you have to set the whoname, description, leader,
and a few other things.

To stat a clan you type
stat clan <clan_name>

Clan files are saved in the /clans directory, and are loaded by placing the 
clan name in the CLANS.LST file.  If for some reason you need a
clan not to load, just remove the name from the file.  This functions just 
like the AREA.LST file.
~

0 GUILDHALLS~
New Guildhall Construction 
--------------------------
Information on construction of a guild hall is contained in the HELP
CONSTRUCT section.  This file will take you step-by-step through the
steps required to construct a guild hall.

Guildhall location are subject to administrative approval.  The admins
will make a judgement call about the location based on its position
relative to other guildhalls, hometowns and other zones, and overall
map layout.

See also: CONSTRUCT
~

0 CONSTRUCT~

Guildhall Construction Rules and Notes

Last Modified: 1/21/99

This guide, written by Ski, should take you through the steps you need to
perform when writing a guildhall for Magma.  It is intended for use with
the DE program, which can be obtained from Github at:
https://github.com/Xangis/magma

This guide assumes you know how to use the DE program.  If you don't, you
shouldn't be making the guildhall.

This guide is broken down into numerous sections.  Type 'help construct1'
for the first section.
~

0 CONSTRUCT1~

1.  Contacting the admins
=========================
Before you start making the hall, you need to contact the Guildhall Admin.
This administrator will give you certain pieces of information you need
when making the zone.  He should give you the following pieces of
information:

1.  Starting vnum for rooms, objs, and mobs.
2.  Zone number
3.  Your association number
4.  A destination room number if you have a portal to a hometown.

You should tell the administrator where you would like the hall to go on the
map.  Guildhalls must be connected to one of the maps (either the overland
map or the underdark map), they must be reached by a "normal" exit (ie no
portals or teleports to the hall), the entrance to the hall must be at
ground level (no flying guildhalls), and they cannot be located within 5
"spaces" of another guildhall.  Goodie guilds cannot put halls in the
underdark, and evils cannot put halls on the main overland continent.

Continued in 'help construct2'
~

0 CONSTRUCT2~

2.  Creating the Guildhall
==========================
The second step is to make a brand new zone using the de program.  Easiest
way to do this is just to type:

de <hallname>  where <filename> should be something like "mowhall" (for the
               Masters of War guildhall).  
               
               Don't call the hall something generic like 'guild' or 'hall'.
               Make the name unique to your faction.
               
DE will bring up a few indicators letting you know it couldn't open any
files (since they don't exist yet).  It will then prompt you for the
starting vnum for rooms, objects, and mobs.  Enter the number that was
given to you by the Guildhall admin.

Enter a name for the zone when prompted.  Use something appropriate, such
as "Masters of War Guildhall".

Enter the zone number that was given to you by the Guildhall admin.  You
should now be in the DE program looking at the first room of the hall.

Continued in 'help construct3'
~

0 CONSTRUCT3~

3.  Editting the zone flags
===========================
Type "edit zone".
The zone name and number should be correct, since you entered them when
  you first created the zone.
Type "C" to edit lifespan values and reset mode.
Type "C" again to edit the reset mode.
Change the value to "0" so the zone never resets.
Type "D" to edit the miscellaneous bits.
The zone should have the "D. No Teleport" bit set.  Nothing else should be
  selected.

Continued in 'help construct4'
~

0 CONSTRUCT4~

4.  Laying out the golem room
=============================
The first room in the guildhall must be the golem room, and it must be
the room that will connect to the map.  This first room can have two
exits: one to the map and one into the hall.  The exit to the map can
be of any direction, but the exit into the hall cannot be a diagonal.

Edit the room and create an exit in the direction that you want to lead
to the map.  Link it to room -1.  The Guildhall admin will link the hall
to the map using this exit, once the guild is approved.

Continued in 'help construct5'
~

0 CONSTRUCT5~

5.  Rules for Rooms
===================
Each room should follow these rules:

Rooms must have an appropriate name and a room description.

The following flags should be chosen.  Make sure nothing else is selected.

     D. Indoors
     G. No Recall
     M. No Precipitation
     P. No Teleport
     X. No Summon
     Y. Guild Room
     Z. Twilight
     2. No gate/planeshift

The "R. Heal" flag may be chosen, but this adds to the cost of the guildhall.

You may only have one healing room per hall.  See the Prices section of
this document to see how much a healing room costs.

The room should have sector type "B. City".

Rooms (except the golem) room can have any number of exits.  Exits may not
have any doors.  Exits must be "reversible", which means if you go east
from one room to get to another, you can go west to get back to the first
room.

Rooms should have a fall percentage chance of 0%, a mana flag of 0, mana
value of 0, current strength of 0, and current direction of 0 (all the
default values).

Continued in 'help construct6'
~

0 CONSTRUCT6~

6. Rules for Golems
===================
Each hall can have up to 4 golems.  Golems must have an appropriate short
name, long name, keywords, and description.  These should correspond to
one another in a logical fashion.  For example, a golem could have:

Short name: 
"&+ga&n &+Gglowing&n &+ggreen&n &+Ggolem&n"
Long name: 
"&+gA golem made of&n &+Gglowing&n &+ggreen stone blocks passage to north.&n"
Keywords:
green golem glowing _guildgolem_ assoc1_n_0 _nomoney_ 
Description: 
&+gA powerful magic has enchanted this solid block of green stone, creating a
powerful guardian that blocks passage to the north.  Occassionally, brilliant
pulses of bright green flash through the substance that makes up this golem,
like blood through veins.

Mobs must have the following keywords:
     golem
     _guildgolem_
     assoc1_N_0 (see below for details)
     _nomoney_

You may not use other keywords to affect the golems, such as _size_ flags.

The assoc1_N_0 keyword varies from hall to hall.  The "1" should be
replaced with your association number, given to you by the Guildhall
admin.  The "N" should be replaced with the exit direction that leads
further into the hall.  The "0" should be left alone.

So, for a guild with association number 4, and an exit leading east into
the hall, each golem would have the keyword:

assoc4_E_0

Remember, you may not have diagonal exits leading further into the hall.

Golems should have the following E. action flags:
     "B. Sentinel"
     "D. Is NPC"
     "G. Stays in zone"
     "L. Memory"
     "M. Can't be paralyzed"
     "N. Can't be summoned"
     "O. Can't be bashed"
     "Z. Breaks charm"
     "1. Protector"

Golems should have the following F. affect1 flags:
     "D. Detect Invis"

Golems should not have any affect2, affect3, or affect4 flags.  Anything
else that golems need is handled by the code.

Golems should be species: "OG (golem)".
Golems should have a hometown of "0 (none)".
Golems should have an alignment of "0".
Golems may only have a class of "1. Warrior", "6. Cleric", or "10.
Sorcerer".

Golems should be level 59.
Golems should have a position and default position of "8 (standing)".
Golems may be neuter, male, or female.

All values in the "M." section of the mob editor should be left at the
default values of 0.

Golems cannot have quest or shop information.

All golems must be placed in the first room of the guildhall.  Golems may
not have equipment.  Golems cannot follow one another.

Continued in 'help construct7'
~

0 CONSTRUCT7~
     
Rules for Shopkeepers
=====================
A guild can have one shop and shopkeeper.

Shopkeepers should have an appropriate short name, long name, keywords,
and description.  These should correspond to each other in a logical
fashion.

Shopkeepers should have the following E. action flags:
     B. Sentinel
     D. Is NPC
